th the Democratic Party while living in the US, and were politically active, they avoided political activity in Ghana and many identified with the Ghanaian party that is modeled after the Republican Party in the US. Taylor dispels some of the incorrect assumptions about African politics and provides readers with an insightful look at how developing nations can embark upon a path toward democratization.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aAfrican American businesspeoplezGhana. 0aAfrican AmericansxPolitical activityzGhana. 0aAfrican AmericansxRelations with Africans. 0aAfrican AmericanszGhanaxHistory. 4aAfrican American Studies : African American Studies. 4aArea Studies : African Studies. 4aCultural Studies : Cultural Studies. 4aHistory : History. 4aPolitics and Law : Political Science. 7aHISTORY / Africa / West.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package 2019z978311149143140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781438474724423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781438474724/original  a978-3-11-149143-1  SUNY Press eBook Package 2019b2019  aGBV-deGruyter-alles